Food Access and Social Determinants of Health Affecting Obesity Rates

Github link: https://nmoore26.github.io/index.html

The Team: Nina Moore, Amy Le Nguyen

Project Goals

Our project seeks to better understand which socioeconomic factors in the USA during 2015 most accurately affect the Obesity percentage rates in each of the States. Obesity is a wide-ranging issue in the United States and there are many unseen factors that contribute to the obesity rates in the USA. To assist us in this study, we have chosen three datasets.

Dataset 1 is:

  • National Obesity Percentages by State (Data.gov): Lists percentages of state population considered obese from a 2015 CDC survey. This serves as the basis for our data analysis.

This dataset is key to our analysis as it provides the obesity percentages in each state in 2015.

Dataset 2 is:

  • Social Determinants of Health Database (Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality): A dataset with measures of 330 social determinants of health across all 50 states, with specificity by county, in 2015. We plan to look at race, median household income, percentage of households that have food stamps, etc.

This dataset is key as it introduces socioeconomic factors that will help us to determine if race is a key factor in the obesity rates seen in each state.

Dataset 3 is:

  • Food Environmental Atlas (USDA): Measures access to food statewide for all 50 states. It considers variables like grocery stores, dollar stores, fast food restaurants, sit-down restaurants in the county.

This dataset is key as it provides data about the access to stores and therefore helps us to determine if the access to nutritious food is a factor in the obesity rates seen in each state.

Through the cleaning and analysis of these three datasets, we seek to answer the following questions:

  1. How do access to grocery stores and restaurants contribute to obesity metrics?
  2. Do median household income or statewide percentage of households with food stamps correlate with obesity?
  3. Are certain populations more or less affected by obesity?
  4. Which race has the highest rate of obesity?
  5. Which race with the lowest access to food has the higher obesity %?
  6. Which counties in a particular state are similar to each other and does a state's mean household income affect the obesity rates?
  7. Are the Median Household Income, Percent Household Foodstamps, and the Adult Diabetes % key determining factors of obesity?

We'll take a look at how populations with low access to food are affected by obesity. In the Food Atlas dataset, 'LACCESS_POP15' records the number of individuals in each county of the US that are said to have low access to food. The raw population counts are not very helpful to us, as states with larger total populations will naturally have a higher low-access population. We need a fairer way to compare between states, so we'll create what we call state_contribution.

In order to properly assess states' rates of low access to food, we'll take the sum of the 'LACCESS_POP15' column to find the total low-access population across the United States. Then, we'll use each state's individual low-access population counts to see what percentage of low-access individuals live in each state. This is what the state_contribution variable is.

In[14]:
# total low-access population across all counties
total_low_access = access_df['LACCESS_POP15'].sum()

# add up low-access population by state
state_low_access = access_df.groupby('State')['LACCESS_POP15'].sum()

# normalize each state's low-access population by total
# this gives a sense of to national contribution
state_contribution = state_low_access / total_low_access

# sort to see which states contribute most to low food access
state_contribution_sorted = state_contribution.sort_values(ascending=False)

# print states with highest and lowest state contributions to low access to food
display(state_contribution_sorted.head())
print('State with largest rate of population with low access to food: ',
      state_contribution_sorted.idxmax(), ', ',
       round(state_contribution_sorted.max() * 100, 2), '%')
print('State with smallest rate of population with low access to food: ',
      state_contribution_sorted.idxmin(), ', ',
      round(state_contribution_sorted.min() * 100, 2), '%')

Using this method, we see that 9.83% of the United States's low-access to food population is located in Texas. In contrast, only 0.02% of the country's population with low access to food is located in Washington, D.C.

We still want to see how state contribution and obesity percentages correlate with each other, however. Since they are on different scales, however (the maximum for state_contribution is 9.83% vs. 36.2% for obesity_perc), so we will z-score standardize the data.

In[15]:
# z-score state contribution
state_contribution_sc = (state_contribution - np.mean(state_contribution)) / np.std(state_contribution)
display(state_contribution_sc.head())

# sort obesity_perc by state name first so that the state contribution and
# obesity percentage data correspond with the same state
obesity_perc = obesity_perc.sort_values("NAME").reset_index(drop=True)

# calculate z-score
obesity_perc["Obesity_sc"] = ((obesity_perc["Obesity"] - np.mean(obesity_perc["Obesity"])) /
                              np.std(obesity_perc["Obesity"]))
display(obesity_perc.head())

Most of the points for each state are close to each other, indicating that obesity rate and low access to food perform similarly on a state scale. For example, the points overlap for Michigan, where it does ~0.5 a standard deviation higher than average when it comes to its low access to food population and ~0.5 a standard deviation higher when it comes to the obesity rate in the state. That is, its state contribution to low access to food performs similarly to its obesity rate. In contrast, Texas interestingly has a very high standardized state contribution to low access to food population but a moderate obesity percentage rate.

This visualization allows us to compare these variables on a state level, but it is difficult to gauge any real correlation between the variables. To do so, we'll simply plot the unstandardized points and find the correlation between the two using seaborn.

In[17]:
# define low-access to food variable from access_df
low_access = access_df.groupby("State", as_index=False)["LACCESS_POP15"].mean()

# merge low_access with obesity_perc
merged = pd.merge(low_access, obesity_perc, left_on="State", right_on="NAME", how="inner")

# calculate correlation value between the two variables
corr_value = merged["LACCESS_POP15"].corr(merged["Obesity"])
print(f"Correlation between low access to food and obesity: {corr_value:.3f}")

# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.regplot(
    data=merged,
    x="LACCESS_POP15",
    y="Obesity",
    scatter_kws={"color": "green", "s": 60},
    line_kws={"color": "purple"}
)
plt.title("Relationship between Low Food Access and Obesity by State")
plt.xlabel("Low Food Access Population (2015)")
plt.ylabel("Obesity Rate (%)")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)
plt.show()

Correlation between low access to food and obesity: -0.439

The correlation between low food access population and obesity rate is -0.439. This means that obesity rates go down within a state as the population with low food access goes up.

This serves as a reminder of why we are exploring social determinants of health on obesity: there are tangible health effects that come with obesity, which are often out of the individual's control.

In[23]:
# get rid of any negative values that may affect the groupby function when averaging

# Replace negatives with NaN only in numeric columns
access_df[access_df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns] = \
    access_df.select_dtypes(include='number').apply(lambda x: x.where(x >= 0, np.nan))

assistance_df[assistance_df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns] = \
    assistance_df.select_dtypes(include='number').apply(lambda x: x.where(x >= 0, np.nan))

diabetes_df[diabetes_df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns] = \
    diabetes_df.select_dtypes(include='number').apply(lambda x: x.where(x >= 0, np.nan))

# Now group by State and take the mean (ignores NaN automatically)
access_3 = access_df.groupby('State', as_index=False).mean(numeric_only=True)
assistance_3 = assistance_df.groupby('State', as_index=False).mean(numeric_only=True)
diabetes_3 = diabetes_df.groupby('State', as_index=False).mean(numeric_only=True)

Now we will employ a correlation matrix on both dataframes to determine which two models we could create that can predict obesity percentage more accurately. However first, we need to create a version of the dataframes without the State column, as a correlation matrix works only on numeric values.

In[35]:
# merged_norace
corr_norace = merged_norace.drop(columns='State').corr()
# merged_race
corr_race = merged_race.drop(columns='State').corr()
In[36]:
# for no race
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.heatmap(corr_norace, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=.5)
plt.title('Correlation Map of Variables (No Race)')
plt.show()

From this correlation heat map, it can be seen that variables that deal with low store access are highly correlated with one another. This is expected, but this correlation matrix cements the idea that store access is a significant factor to consider. When considering factors that affect obesity specifically, 'Median Household Income' and 'Percent Household Foodstamps' seem to have moderate-high correlations.

In[37]:
# for race
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.heatmap(corr_race, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=.5)
plt.title('Correlation Map of Variables (Race)')
plt.show()

The correlation heat maps above show that race may not be a very significant factor in percentages of obesity in a state. This is shown by how there are fewer variables with a high correlation value in the merged dataframe focusing just on race-based scoioeconomic factors that the dataframe that focuses on non-race based socioeconomic factors.

Model Questions

Given the above two correlation matrices, we are interested in creating 3 models in which the relationship between

  • Median Household Income vs Obesity %

  • Percent Household Foodstamps vs Obesity %

are examined. In these two models the independant variables are Median Household Income and Percent Household Foodstamps. The dependant variable in both models is Obesity %. We are additionally interested in modeling the relationship between

  • Adult Diabetes % vs Obesity %.

Since we are dealing with numeric data a linear regression model is suitable for all 3 models. Our goal is to examine which of the three independant variables more accurately can predict Obesity %. These models shall be implemented at a later time.
